Europe Needs to Restart Its Immigration Policy
Brussels — More than 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
Meanwhile, the rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching all summer for safe ports where their passengers can disembark.
Refugee and migrant camps on the Greek island of Lesbos are overcrowded, and similar conditions exist in other camps in Libya.
Turkey has torn up the 2016 agreement that prevented migrants from entering the EU.
Although Europe wants to help migrants and respects international law, it does not want overcrowding.
Between 2015 and 2016, the number of refugees and migrants flowing into the EU surged — many of them fleeing the Syrian conflict — which greatly affected trust within the EU.
The massive influx of migrants eroded confidence in government management of the EU's external borders and asylum, and also highlighted the futility of cooperation with countries of origin.
As a result, immigration has become a political football, a favorite of populists.
Under the leadership of President Ursula von der Leyen, the new European Commission must regain control of the immigration issue while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
To this end, the EU needs to revise its guidelines in four areas and mobilize member states to act in Europe's interest.
First, the EU must urgently secure its external borders, which is a prerequisite for keeping internal borders open.
Any country where people can freely move internally, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, would not outsource control of its external borders to a single state or region.
Controlling the EU's external borders must be a collective task and also a national task.
The EU's border and coast guard agency, Frontex, must be further strengthened and should be deployed joint security forces with member states — including along coastlines and at airports.
The EU must also restart Operation Sophia to combat illegal immigration in the Mediterranean.
Secondly, Europe needs to treat economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Mixing them has brought the asylum system close to collapse; treating them separately helps ensure that migrants concerned about their safety can voice their concerns while their rights are protected.
Addressing the EU's real economic and social needs requires effective blue or green card policies for economic migrants and the implementation of an overall immigration target.
This must not wait until the next immigration crisis to consider introducing these mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break the taboo.
First, the number of economic migrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a matter of common interest.
Second, policies must clearly define which migrants are welcome.
Third, member states must answer what EU assistance is needed to ensure a smooth immigration process.
Finally, visas and work permits must be brought to the forefront to facilitate the return of illegal migrants to their countries of origin.
Indeed, according to the EU treaties, member states need to manage immigrants coming from outside the EU themselves.
However, if governments reach an agreement on overall EU immigration targets, it would be a major step forward.
In turn, member states could specify the source countries and specific requirements for economic migrants they want, as well as the EU budget resources needed to accommodate them.
This way, the right to accept immigrants would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has long had a proactive immigration policy, selecting immigrants based on criteria such as country of origin, skill level, and age.
Europe can do the same.
Third, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First, the one-size-fits-all requirement for compulsory distribution of asylum seekers within the EU must be abandoned.
This requirement undermines the atmosphere within the EU, but it could still be feasible if the border, asylum, and immigration systems are fully effective.
Furthermore, frontline EU member states cannot be expected to tackle alone the issue of illegal immigrants crossing external borders.
The refugee camps are overcrowded, and migrants are subjected to abuse by authorities or driven northward.
The responsibility of the first EU member state where migrants arrive must be supplemented by EU solidarity.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to streamline the behavior and management capacity of national asylum agencies.
Only in this way can national decisions be respected throughout the Schengen area, ensuring the integrity of the cross-border travel zone.
Once the behavior and management capacity of national asylum agencies are streamlined, the process for handling asylum applications can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should build stronger win-win cooperation with source and transit countries.
These connections are crucial for repatriating migrants who are legally prohibited from entering the EU.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all foreign policy tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as programs in areas such as security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's immigration objectives, as well as skill cooperation preparing for European jobs, can be offered to third countries seeking stable remittances.
At the same time, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
This includes the population explosion in sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; ethnic conflicts; and a lack of job opportunities.
The EU's aid should focus on reshaping stability and reducing risks by supporting security, community resilience, and good governance.
Success in this area can make investments safer, unlock private and domestic finance, thereby enabling national economic growth, job creation, and providing alternatives to migration.
The new European Commission has an opportunity to move the EU away from instinctive reactions to the migration crisis and towards a more coherent and sustainable approach, both internally and externally.
We must never miss this opportunity.
